{
  "Who proposed the hypothesis of continental drift in 1915?": "",
  "Harry Hess": "",
  "James Hutton": "",
  "Charles Darwin": "",
  "Alfred Wegener": "",
  "Alfred Wegener, a German meteorologist, proposed the continental drift hypothesis in 1915. He suggested that all continents were once joined in a single supercontinent called Pangaea, but his hypothesis was largely rejected at the time because he could not explain the mechanism driving the movement.": "",
  "What was the name of the supercontinent that Wegener believed once existed?": "",
  "Laurasia": "",
  "Rodinia": "",
  "Pangaea": "",
  "Gondwana": "",
  "Pangaea, meaning 'all lands' in Greek, was the supercontinent that Wegener proposed existed about 200–300 million years ago. It later broke apart into the continents we see today, with Laurasia forming the northern continents and Gondwana forming the southern continents.": "",
  "At which type of plate boundary do tectonic plates move apart from each other?": "",
  "Subduction zone": "",
  "Convergent boundary": "",
  "Transform boundary": "",
  "Divergent boundary": "",
  "At divergent boundaries, tectonic plates move apart from each other. Magma rises from the mantle to fill the gap, creating new oceanic crust. Mid-ocean ridges are the most prominent features formed at divergent boundaries.": "",
  "What happens at a convergent plate boundary when an oceanic plate meets a continental plate?": "",
  "Both plates slide past each other horizontally": "",
  "The continental plate subducts beneath the oceanic plate": "",
  "Both plates move apart and new crust forms": "",
  "The oceanic plate subducts beneath the continental plate": "",
  "When an oceanic plate converges with a continental plate, the denser oceanic plate is forced beneath the lighter continental plate in a process called subduction. This creates deep ocean trenches, volcanic mountain ranges, and earthquake activity.": "",
  "Who proposed the seafloor spreading hypothesis?": "",
  "Arthur Holmes": "",
  "J. Tuzo Wilson": "",
  "Harry Hess, a Princeton geologist and Navy officer, proposed the seafloor spreading hypothesis in 1962. He suggested that new oceanic crust forms at mid-ocean ridges and moves outward, eventually being recycled at subduction zones. This provided the mechanism Wegener's hypothesis had lacked.": "",
  "What type of plate boundary is characterized by plates sliding horizontally past each other?": "",
  "Hotspot boundary": "",
  "At transform boundaries, tectonic plates slide horizontally past each other. No crust is created or destroyed at these boundaries. The San Andreas Fault in California is a well-known example of a continental transform boundary.": "",
  "Magnetic striping on the ocean floor provides evidence for:": "",
  "Ocean currents changing direction over time": "",
  "Seafloor spreading and magnetic pole reversals": "",
  "Changes in ocean water temperature": "",
  "Meteor impacts on the ocean floor": "",
  "As new oceanic crust forms at mid-ocean ridges, iron minerals in the cooling lava align with Earth's magnetic field. Since the magnetic poles periodically reverse, the resulting pattern creates symmetrical stripes of normal and reversed polarity on either side of the ridge, confirming seafloor spreading.": "",
  "A subduction zone is an area where:": "",
  "Two plates slide past each other": "",
  "Magma rises through a hotspot in the mantle": "",
  "Two plates pull apart and new crust forms": "",
  "One plate is forced beneath another plate": "",
  "A subduction zone is a convergent boundary where one tectonic plate dives beneath another into the mantle. The subducting plate is typically oceanic crust, which is denser than continental crust. Subduction zones are associated with deep ocean trenches, volcanic arcs, and powerful earthquakes.": "",
  "Which of the following is evidence Wegener used to support continental drift?": "",
  "Magnetic striping patterns on the ocean floor": "",
  "Matching fossils on continents separated by oceans": "",
  "GPS measurements of plate movement": "",
  "Sonar mapping of the mid-ocean ridges": "",
  "Wegener used several lines of evidence including matching fossils of organisms like Mesosaurus and Glossopteris found on continents now separated by oceans. He also cited the jigsaw-puzzle fit of continental coastlines, matching rock formations, and glacial evidence across multiple continents.": "",
  "New oceanic crust is created at:": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridges": "",
  "Subduction zones": "",
  "Transform faults": "",
  "Continental margins": "",
  "New oceanic crust is created at mid-ocean ridges where tectonic plates diverge. Magma from the mantle rises to fill the gap, cools, and solidifies into new basaltic crust. This process of seafloor spreading continuously adds new material to the ocean floor.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'seafloor spreading'?": "",
  "The process by which continents drift across ocean basins": "",
  "The process by which new oceanic crust forms at mid-ocean ridges and moves outward": "",
  "The sinking of oceanic crust at continental margins": "",
  "The erosion of the seafloor by deep ocean currents": "",
  "Seafloor spreading is the process by which magma rises at mid-ocean ridges, cools to form new oceanic crust, and then moves away from the ridge as more new crust is created behind it. This mechanism drives the movement of tectonic plates across Earth's surface.": "",
  "What does the term 'subduction' mean?": "",
  "The process by which one tectonic plate descends beneath another into the mantle": "",
  "The formation of new crust at a ridge": "",
  "The accumulation of sediment on the ocean floor": "",
  "The horizontal sliding of plates past each other": "",
  "Subduction occurs when one tectonic plate is forced beneath another and descends into the Earth's mantle. The subducting plate melts as it goes deeper, and this process recycles oceanic crust, forms deep ocean trenches, and generates volcanic activity.": "",
  "The term 'paleomagnetism' refers to:": "",
  "The magnetic properties of ocean water": "",
  "The record of Earth's past magnetic field preserved in rocks": "",
  "The use of magnets in ocean exploration equipment": "",
  "The current strength of Earth's magnetic field": "",
  "Paleomagnetism is the study of the record of Earth's magnetic field preserved in ferromagnetic minerals within rocks. As rocks form, iron-bearing minerals align with the prevailing magnetic field, creating a permanent record that scientists use to trace plate movements and magnetic reversals.": "",
  "What is a 'magnetic reversal'?": "",
  "The rotation of Earth's axis relative to the sun": "",
  "The deflection of ocean currents by magnetic forces": "",
  "A change in Earth's magnetic field where the north and south magnetic poles switch": "",
  "The weakening of Earth's magnetic field during solar storms": "",
  "A magnetic reversal occurs when Earth's magnetic north and south poles switch positions. These reversals are recorded in the rocks of the ocean floor as alternating stripes of normal and reversed polarity, providing key evidence for the theory of seafloor spreading.": "",
  "A 'convergent boundary' is defined as:": "",
  "A place where two tectonic plates come together": "",
  "A place where two tectonic plates move apart": "",
  "A place where plates slide past one another": "",
  "A place where magma erupts from a hotspot": "",
  "A convergent boundary is where two tectonic plates move toward each other and collide. Depending on the types of plates involved (oceanic vs. continental), convergent boundaries can produce subduction zones, volcanic arcs, mountain ranges, or deep ocean trenches.": "",
  "What is the lithosphere?": "",
  "The rigid outer layer of the Earth consisting of the crust and upper mantle": "",
  "The gaseous atmosphere surrounding the Earth": "",
  "The partially molten layer beneath the crust": "",
  "The liquid outer core of the Earth": "",
  "The lithosphere is Earth's rigid outermost shell, composed of the crust and the uppermost portion of the mantle. It is broken into tectonic plates that float on the underlying asthenosphere. The lithosphere includes both oceanic and continental crust.": "",
  "The asthenosphere is best described as:": "",
  "The outermost rigid layer of the Earth": "",
  "The ocean crust at mid-ocean ridges": "",
  "A partially molten, ductile layer of the upper mantle beneath the lithosphere": "",
  "The solid inner core of the Earth": "",
  "The asthenosphere is a partially molten, ductile zone in the upper mantle that lies beneath the rigid lithosphere. Its ability to flow slowly allows tectonic plates to move across Earth's surface, driven by convection currents in the mantle.": "",
  "What is 'Pangaea' in the context of plate tectonics?": "",
  "An ancient ocean that surrounded all continents": "",
  "A theory about how the ocean floor is recycled": "",
  "The name of the first mid-ocean ridge discovered": "",
  "The supercontinent that existed when all landmasses were joined together": "",
  "Pangaea was the supercontinent that formed about 335 million years ago and began to break apart around 175 million years ago. It included all of Earth's major landmasses and was surrounded by a global ocean called Panthalassa.": "",
  "What does the term 'plate tectonics' refer to?": "",
  "A method for predicting tsunamis": "",
  "The theory that Earth's lithosphere is divided into plates that move, interact, and reshape the surface": "",
  "The study of how earthquakes form in the ocean": "",
  "The process of volcanic island formation": "",
  "Plate tectonics is the unifying theory that Earth's outer shell (lithosphere) is divided into several large and small plates that move, interact at their boundaries, and continually reshape the Earth's surface. It explains earthquakes, volcanism, mountain building, and the distribution of fossils.": "",
  "A 'divergent boundary' is where:": "",
  "One plate is forced under another": "",
  "Two plates move apart and new crust is formed": "",
  "Two plates collide and crumple upward": "",
  "Two plates grind past each other horizontally": "",
  "A divergent boundary is a location where two tectonic plates are moving away from each other. As the plates separate, magma rises from the mantle to fill the gap, creating new oceanic crust. Mid-ocean ridges are the primary features formed at divergent boundaries.": "",
  "A scientist finds identical fossils of a freshwater reptile on the coasts of South America and Africa, continents now separated by the Atlantic Ocean. What is the best explanation for this observation?": "",
  "The reptile swam across the Atlantic Ocean": "",
  "The fossils were carried to both continents by ocean currents": "",
  "Identical species evolved independently on separate continents": "",
  "The continents were once joined, and the species lived across both landmasses before they separated": "",
  "The presence of identical freshwater reptile fossils on two continents separated by an ocean is strong evidence that the continents were once connected. A freshwater species could not have crossed a saltwater ocean, so the best explanation is that South America and Africa were once part of the same landmass (Pangaea).": "",
  "A research team discovers that the age of the ocean floor increases with distance from a mid-ocean ridge, and the magnetic polarity of the rock alternates in symmetrical stripes on either side of the ridge. What theory does this evidence support?": "",
  "Seafloor spreading": "",
  "Continental drift only": "",
  "Glacial rebound": "",
  "Hotspot volcanism": "",
  "Symmetrical magnetic stripes on either side of a mid-ocean ridge, combined with seafloor age increasing with distance from the ridge, provide direct evidence for seafloor spreading. New crust forms at the ridge and records the current magnetic polarity, then moves outward as newer crust forms behind it.": "",
  "Two oceanic plates converge, and the older, denser plate subducts beneath the younger one. Over millions of years, what features would you expect to form in this area?": "",
  "A mid-ocean ridge and rift valley": "",
  "A transform fault with frequent shallow earthquakes": "",
  "A deep ocean trench and a volcanic island arc": "",
  "A continental mountain range with no volcanic activity": "",
  "When two oceanic plates converge, the older and denser plate subducts, forming a deep ocean trench. The subducting plate melts as it descends into the mantle, and the resulting magma rises to form a chain of volcanic islands called an island arc parallel to the trench.": "",
  "GPS data shows that two stations on opposite sides of the Atlantic Ocean are moving apart at about 2.5 cm per year. If the Atlantic Ocean is approximately 5,000 km wide, roughly how long ago did the ocean begin to form?": "",
  "1 billion years ago": "",
  "50 million years ago": "",
  "500 million years ago": "",
  "200 million years ago": "",
  "At 2.5 cm/year, the total distance of 5,000 km (500,000,000 cm) divided by 2.5 cm/year equals 200 million years. This estimate aligns with geological evidence that the Atlantic Ocean began forming about 180–200 million years ago as Pangaea broke apart.": "",
  "A volcanic island chain in the Pacific Ocean has islands that get progressively older as you move northwest, with an active volcano only at the southeastern end. What geological process best explains this pattern?": "",
  "Transform faulting along a fracture zone": "",
  "A hotspot beneath a moving tectonic plate": "",
  "Seafloor spreading at a divergent boundary": "",
  "Subduction at a convergent boundary": "",
  "This pattern describes a hotspot island chain like Hawaii. A stationary mantle plume creates volcanoes on the overlying plate, but as the plate moves northwest, each volcano is carried away from the heat source and becomes extinct, while a new volcano forms over the hotspot.": "",
  "Scientists drill into the ocean floor and find that the deepest sediment layers near a mid-ocean ridge are only 2 million years old, while sediment layers near the continental margin are 150 million years old. What does this tell us?": "",
  "The ocean floor near the ridge is younger because it was more recently created by seafloor spreading": "",
  "Volcanic activity destroyed older sediments near the ridge": "",
  "Sedimentation rates are faster near mid-ocean ridges": "",
  "The continental margin is closer to the original location of Pangaea": "",
  "The increasing age of ocean floor sediments away from mid-ocean ridges is direct evidence of seafloor spreading. New crust forms at the ridge, so it is youngest there. As the crust moves outward over millions of years, it accumulates older and thicker sediment layers.": "",
  "An earthquake occurs at a depth of 300 km beneath the ocean floor near a deep ocean trench. What type of plate boundary and process is most likely responsible?": "",
  "Hotspot volcanism beneath the plate": "",
  "Divergent boundary with seafloor spreading": "",
  "Convergent boundary with subduction": "",
  "Transform boundary with lateral plate movement": "",
  "Deep-focus earthquakes (greater than 300 km depth) are characteristic of subduction zones at convergent boundaries. As the subducting plate descends into the mantle, the immense pressure and friction generate earthquakes at progressively greater depths along the Wadati-Benioff zone.": "",
  "A geologist compares the rock types on the western coast of Africa and the eastern coast of South America and finds matching sequences of rock layers and mineral compositions. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Ocean currents transported rocks between the continents": "",
  "Similar climates on both coasts produced identical rocks": "",
  "The two coastlines were once joined as part of Pangaea and shared the same geological formations": "",
  "Volcanic activity created identical rocks on both sides of the Atlantic": "",
  "Matching rock sequences across the Atlantic provide strong evidence that Africa and South America were once connected as part of Pangaea. When the supercontinent rifted apart, the geological formations were split, leaving matching halves on each continent's opposing coast.": "",
  "A student argues that continental drift cannot be real because the continents are too massive to move. How would a modern geologist counter this argument?": "",
  "The continents are not actually moving; only the ocean floor moves": "",
  "Gravity from the moon pulls the continents across the surface": "",
  "Convection currents in the mantle provide the driving force that moves entire tectonic plates, including continents": "",
  "Continental drift has been disproven by modern evidence": "",
  "Modern plate tectonic theory explains that convection currents in the asthenosphere, combined with ridge push and slab pull forces, provide the energy to move tectonic plates. The continents ride passively on these plates, which is why Wegener's original hypothesis lacked a mechanism.": "",
  "A magnetic survey of the ocean floor reveals that the pattern of magnetic stripes is symmetrical on both sides of a mid-ocean ridge, but the stripes on the eastern side are 20% wider than those on the western side over the same time period. What can you conclude?": "",
  "The eastern side has thicker sediment covering the magnetic signal": "",
  "The magnetic field is stronger on the eastern side": "",
  "The eastern plate is spreading faster than the western plate": "",
  "Volcanic activity is less frequent on the eastern side": "",
  "Wider magnetic stripes on one side indicate that side of the plate is moving faster, creating more crust in the same time period. Spreading rates are not always symmetrical; asymmetric spreading is common and means one plate moves away from the ridge faster than the other.": ""
}